ğŸ”¹ Backend (Node.js + Express + MongoDB)

Your backend is responsible for storing chat threads, handling API requests, and fetching OpenAI responses.

1. server.js (main entry file)

express.json() â†’ parses incoming JSON requests (so your API can read { message, threadId }).

cors() â†’ enables cross-origin access (your frontend at localhost:5173 or similar can call the backend at localhost:7000).

mongoose.connect() â†’ connects app with MongoDB (cloud/local).

app.use("/api", chatRoutes) â†’ mounts all your routes (thread management + chat handling).

ğŸ“Œ Important topics here:

Middleware (CORS, JSON body parser)

MongoDB connection via Mongoose

Modular routing in Express

2. chat.js (routes)

This file defines the endpoints.

POST /test â†’ creates a dummy thread to check DB connection.

GET /thread â†’ fetches all threads sorted by last updated.

GET /thread/:threadId â†’ fetches messages of a single thread.

DELETE /thread/:threadId â†’ deletes a thread by its ID.

POST /chat â†’ main logic:

If thread doesnâ€™t exist â†’ create new one with the first user message.

Else â†’ push new message into existing thread.

Call getOpenAIAPIResponse(message) â†’ gets AI response.

Save both user + assistant messages into MongoDB.

Send assistantâ€™s reply to frontend.

ğŸ“Œ Important topics here:

REST API design (GET, POST, DELETE)

Mongoose CRUD (findOne, save, findOneAndDelete, find)

Async/await error handling

Schema structure (Thread model with message: [{ role, content }])

Integration with external API (OpenAI)

ğŸ”¹ Frontend (React)

Your frontend handles UI + state management + API communication.

1. App.jsx

Provides global state using MyContext.

Stores data like prompt, reply, currThreadId, prevChats, allThreads.

Renders Sidebar and ChatWindow.

ğŸ“Œ Important topics here:

React Context API (state sharing across components)

UUID (uuidv1) for creating unique thread IDs

2. Sidebar.jsx

Fetches all threads from /api/thread.

Displays thread titles in history.

Clicking â†’ fetches thread messages (changeThread).

Trash icon â†’ deletes thread (deleteThread).

â€œNew Chatâ€ button â†’ resets context + generates a new thread ID.

ğŸ“Œ Important topics here:

Fetch API calls (GET/DELETE)

Conditional rendering (highlight selected thread)

State reset on new chat

Event bubbling & e.stopPropagation()

3. ChatWindow.jsx

Navbar with dropdown (profile/settings/logout).

Displays chat area (<Chat />).

Input box for typing messages.

getReply() â†’ sends { threadId, message } to backend (/api/chat).

Receives assistant reply â†’ updates prevChats.

Shows loading spinner (ScaleLoader) while waiting.

ğŸ“Œ Important topics here:

Controlled components (input value={prompt})

Async fetch with POST request

Updating state arrays with old + new messages

Loader/UX improvements

4. Chat.jsx

Displays chat history (prevChats).

Renders user messages normally, assistant messages with Markdown + syntax highlighting (react-markdown, rehype-highlight).

Implements typing effect: assistant reply shows word by word.

ğŸ“Œ Important topics here:

Conditional rendering based on role (user vs assistant).

Markdown rendering in React.

useEffect for side effects (typing animation).

ğŸ”¹ How the Flow Works

You type a message in ChatWindow.

React sends { message, threadId } to Express (/api/chat).

Backend checks if thread exists in MongoDB:

If no â†’ create a new thread.

If yes â†’ push new message.

Backend calls OpenAI â†’ gets assistant response.

Saves conversation (user + assistant) into MongoDB.

Sends reply back â†’ React updates prevChats.

Sidebar updates with thread list from DB.

You can delete threads or switch between them.

ğŸ”¹ Big Impact Topics (things that make this project professional)

React Context API â†’ avoids prop drilling, global state for chat.

Mongoose schema + CRUD â†’ structured chat storage.

REST API design â†’ clean separation of frontend/backend.

Integration with OpenAI API â†’ real AI responses.

Markdown + syntax highlighting â†’ makes assistant responses readable.

Typing effect + loader â†’ better UX.

Thread management (create/delete/switch) â†’ production-like feature.

